    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre connection between two or more quantum particles, where their fates become linked regardless of the distance separating them. Measuring a property of one entangled particle instantly influences the corresponding property of the other. Unlike classical correlation, such as knowing one sock in a pair is blue, entanglement implies a shared, indefinite state until a measurement is made. This non-local interdependence is what makes it fundamentally different from everyday correlations.",
      "source": "target",
