    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why do they use that word specifically? is there something actually weird or unexplained about how the information transfers?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein famously called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it appears to imply instantaneous communication faster than the speed of light. The \"spooky\" part stems from the idea that measuring one particle seems to instantaneously affect another across vast distances. However, crucially, this effect cannot be used to transmit actual information faster than light, preserving Einstein's theory of relativity. The correlation is instant, but controlled communication is not.",
      "source": "target",
