    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if we cant use it to send info, then how does the other particle \"know\" what happened to the first one instantly? like is there some kind of hidden mechanism or something that we just havent discovered yet?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Currently, the consensus in physics is that there is no hidden mechanism needed; the correlation is intrinsic to the quantum state itself. The particles don't \"communicate\" in the classical sense; rather, they share a single, unified quantum state from the moment they become entangled. When you measure one particle, you are effectively forcing the entire shared state to collapse instantaneously, fixing the outcome for the distant partner simultaneously.",
      "source": "target",
